00:00:25.790 --> 00:00:29.600
HUGH MCMANUS: Earl introduced
to you the concept of Lean

00:00:29.600 --> 00:00:33.020
and made the assertion
that lean isn't

00:00:33.020 --> 00:00:37.560
so much a collection of tools as
a way of thinking about things.

00:00:37.560 --> 00:00:40.070
So what we're going
to do now, actually,

00:00:40.070 --> 00:00:43.370
in two parts, one
before lunch, one after,

00:00:43.370 --> 00:00:47.960
is introduce you to the basics
of that way of thinking.

00:00:47.960 --> 00:00:50.570
So that's why we call
this module Lean Thinking.

00:00:50.570 --> 00:00:54.210
What we're going to do first
is talk about processes.

00:00:54.210 --> 00:00:59.090
And if Lean thinking has one
really important component,

00:00:59.090 --> 00:01:01.730
if you walk away from here
with one idea in your head,

00:01:01.730 --> 00:01:04.760
it's to think about
work as a process which

00:01:04.760 --> 00:01:08.030
can be improved, so we're going
to spend a little bit of time

00:01:08.030 --> 00:01:10.590
thinking about
what is a process,

00:01:10.590 --> 00:01:12.950
how can we think about
processes, how can we map

00:01:12.950 --> 00:01:17.090
processes, how can we create
visual representations of them,

00:01:17.090 --> 00:01:20.150
and how we can think about
value in that context.

00:01:20.150 --> 00:01:22.310
We're going to look at
the fundamental Lean

00:01:22.310 --> 00:01:25.610
principles of Womack and
Jones, which are essentially

00:01:25.610 --> 00:01:29.000
how can we think about
improving the process in kind

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:30.410
of an organized way.

00:01:30.410 --> 00:01:33.320
And then we're going to
walk through a set of tools

00:01:33.320 --> 00:01:36.290
which, over the course of
the next couple of days,

00:01:36.290 --> 00:01:38.660
we will dive deeper into.

00:01:38.660 --> 00:01:41.760
For now, with the
exception of mapping,

00:01:41.760 --> 00:01:44.960
which we're actually going
to do in some detail,

00:01:44.960 --> 00:01:46.730
we'll walk through
the tools relatively

00:01:46.730 --> 00:01:49.820
quickly just to sort of give
you an introduction to them.

00:01:49.820 --> 00:01:55.340
Again, those will be reinforced
as the course goes on.

00:01:55.340 --> 00:01:58.970
So what do we mean by a process?

00:01:58.970 --> 00:02:03.410
Simply put, it's an action
or a series of actions

00:02:03.410 --> 00:02:05.750
that transforms something.

00:02:05.750 --> 00:02:08.120
We have an input, some
kind of process that

00:02:08.120 --> 00:02:10.820
transforms it into an output.

00:02:10.820 --> 00:02:13.250
If we want to expand the
definition a little bit more,

00:02:13.250 --> 00:02:16.310
we can also think about
where the inputs come from.

00:02:16.310 --> 00:02:20.390
A manufacturing-derived
terminology is suppliers.

00:02:20.390 --> 00:02:21.980
That's actually
kind of dangerous

00:02:21.980 --> 00:02:24.500
because in a service
thing, that may actually

00:02:24.500 --> 00:02:26.810
be the customer
that has a request,

00:02:26.810 --> 00:02:28.160
or it may be somebody else.

00:02:28.160 --> 00:02:31.940
It may not necessarily be a
supplier in the material sense.

00:02:31.940 --> 00:02:34.940
But there is a place where
the inputs come from,

00:02:34.940 --> 00:02:38.510
a set of defined inputs, instead
of defined transformations,

00:02:38.510 --> 00:02:42.000
and the outputs
go to a customer.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:46.990
So let's talk about a
customer a little bit.

00:02:46.990 --> 00:02:49.240
What happens to the
outputs of a process?

00:02:49.240 --> 00:02:51.270
They go to a customer.

00:02:51.270 --> 00:02:54.240
Again, just like
supplier, the terminology,

00:02:54.240 --> 00:02:56.640
we've got to be careful
not to get too hung up on.

00:02:56.640 --> 00:03:00.900
Customer may be customer in the
sort of retail sense, somebody

00:03:00.900 --> 00:03:02.340
who buys something.

00:03:02.340 --> 00:03:07.300
Or it may be somebody else who
gets value out of the process.

00:03:07.300 --> 00:03:10.980
So external customers are
really that retail customer.

00:03:10.980 --> 00:03:13.830
The customer is
the people who pay

00:03:13.830 --> 00:03:16.800
for the process to take place.

00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:19.938
They may or may not
be the end user.

00:03:19.938 --> 00:03:22.230
There are plenty of examples
in the aerospace business,

00:03:22.230 --> 00:03:24.450
for the engineering
side of the room,

00:03:24.450 --> 00:03:27.600
of customers, for example,
government acquisition,

00:03:27.600 --> 00:03:30.960
the people who buy things are
not the people who use them.

00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:33.390
So there's even
there a distinction

00:03:33.390 --> 00:03:38.200
between the purchasing customer
and the end user customer.

00:03:38.200 --> 00:03:41.910
In addition, in many
complex processes,

00:03:41.910 --> 00:03:44.770
you may actually be working
for an internal customer.

00:03:44.770 --> 00:03:48.060
So a given step in a
more complicated process

00:03:48.060 --> 00:03:49.650
may actually be
working for somebody

00:03:49.650 --> 00:03:50.950
inside the organization.

00:03:50.950 --> 00:03:55.170
A classic case of that
in aerospace engineering

00:03:55.170 --> 00:03:56.800
operations.

00:03:56.800 --> 00:03:59.260
Sometimes you do engineering
for outside customers.

00:03:59.260 --> 00:04:01.990
Most of the time you
do it for customers

00:04:01.990 --> 00:04:04.190
within your organization.

00:04:04.190 --> 00:04:06.260
In the health care side,
there's an awful lot

00:04:06.260 --> 00:04:08.990
of service provision
which are not directly

00:04:08.990 --> 00:04:13.190
affecting the patient but
that are necessary, say,

00:04:13.190 --> 00:04:14.780
to keep the hospital going.

00:04:14.780 --> 00:04:19.250
So thinking about customers
with a little bit of nuance

00:04:19.250 --> 00:04:20.550
is necessary.

00:04:20.550 --> 00:04:23.210
The other thing that we want
to make sure we don't get too

00:04:23.210 --> 00:04:26.120
caught up in the
words is the fact

00:04:26.120 --> 00:04:29.000
that our customers
also often provide some

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:30.950
of the inputs to our process.

00:04:30.950 --> 00:04:33.230
So actually, in a classic
retail transaction,

00:04:33.230 --> 00:04:36.800
the customer has a need, which
is an input to our process,

00:04:36.800 --> 00:04:39.830
as well as being
the ones who receive

00:04:39.830 --> 00:04:42.290
the output of the process.

00:04:42.290 --> 00:04:44.500
So how do we
visualize a process?

00:04:44.500 --> 00:04:46.330
Very general question.

00:04:46.330 --> 00:04:49.590
A good method is
process mapping,

00:04:49.590 --> 00:04:52.110
is to try to get
our brains wrapped

00:04:52.110 --> 00:04:55.740
around what goes on
inside our work process

00:04:55.740 --> 00:04:57.990
through a simple map.

00:04:57.990 --> 00:05:00.130
There's a couple
of examples here.

00:05:00.130 --> 00:05:01.660
This one is close to my heart.

00:05:01.660 --> 00:05:06.180
This is an aerospace engineering
drawing release process.

00:05:06.180 --> 00:05:08.413
This is a before Lean.

00:05:08.413 --> 00:05:10.080
It's actually, from
an engineering point

00:05:10.080 --> 00:05:12.460
of view, a simple process.

00:05:12.460 --> 00:05:15.540
But when you map it out in
the sort of legacy state,

00:05:15.540 --> 00:05:16.870
it doesn't look so simple.

00:05:16.870 --> 00:05:18.600
In fact, it looks
very confusing.

00:05:18.600 --> 00:05:20.340
And this is near
and dear to my heart

00:05:20.340 --> 00:05:23.490
because I spent 10 years
working in that box.

00:05:23.490 --> 00:05:24.240
You can't read it.

00:05:24.240 --> 00:05:25.890
That's stress analysis.

00:05:25.890 --> 00:05:27.990
And notice that's the one
that all the lines come

00:05:27.990 --> 00:05:29.580
in and out of.

00:05:29.580 --> 00:05:32.338
So the task actually turned
out to be very simple there,

00:05:32.338 --> 00:05:34.380
but the interactions with
the rest of the process

00:05:34.380 --> 00:05:39.780
were very confusing in
the old, pre-Lean state.

00:05:39.780 --> 00:05:42.720
Here, interestingly,
is a before picture,

00:05:42.720 --> 00:05:45.180
and Earl can probably comment
on this a little more,

00:05:45.180 --> 00:05:48.195
for heart attack treatment.

00:05:48.195 --> 00:05:50.320
This one doesn't look too
bad compared to that one.

00:05:50.320 --> 00:05:52.080
It's sort of more
or less linear.

00:05:52.080 --> 00:05:54.060
There seems to be
some sort of steps,

00:05:54.060 --> 00:05:57.550
probably involving different
people working on the patient.

00:05:57.550 --> 00:05:59.310
But apparently
that was pre-Lean.

00:05:59.310 --> 00:06:01.830
So apparently that
process could be improved.

00:06:01.830 --> 00:06:04.410
AUDIENCE: Problem with that
process was it took too long.

00:06:04.410 --> 00:06:06.060
HUGH MCMANUS: OK,
too many steps.

00:06:06.060 --> 00:06:07.410
So it's organized here.

00:06:07.410 --> 00:06:10.140
We can see a pretty clear path.

00:06:10.140 --> 00:06:12.810
But lots and lots of steps.

00:06:12.810 --> 00:06:14.520
So took too long.

00:06:14.520 --> 00:06:16.770
That's easy to understand.

00:06:16.770 --> 00:06:22.780
This one, yeah, more complex set
of problems with that process.

00:06:22.780 --> 00:06:25.690
In any case, the
point here is not

00:06:25.690 --> 00:06:28.360
to is not to go too deep on
the individual processes,

00:06:28.360 --> 00:06:31.870
but to get the point across that
in order to improve a process,

00:06:31.870 --> 00:06:35.440
you have to understand it, and
that one good way to understand

00:06:35.440 --> 00:06:40.000
it is visually, and
maps help us with that.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:41.680
So here's an example.

00:06:41.680 --> 00:06:43.420
It's not even a
very good example,

00:06:43.420 --> 00:06:45.320
but it's an intuitive example.

00:06:45.320 --> 00:06:47.440
Most people would understand it.

00:06:47.440 --> 00:06:48.970
I want a hot dog.

00:06:48.970 --> 00:06:50.290
Or my kids want a hot dog.

00:06:50.290 --> 00:06:52.510
That's usually what
happens on the weekends.

00:06:52.510 --> 00:06:53.840
Dad, can we have a hot dog?

00:06:53.840 --> 00:06:58.960
So my customer, the
kids, order a hot dog.

00:06:58.960 --> 00:07:00.970
So they're providing
input to the process

00:07:00.970 --> 00:07:03.410
as well as being
the output customer.

00:07:03.410 --> 00:07:05.260
They're kind of in a loop there.

00:07:05.260 --> 00:07:07.810
So then the question
is, do I have hot dogs?

00:07:07.810 --> 00:07:09.333
So I go look in the pantry.

00:07:09.333 --> 00:07:10.750
Why the hot dogs
are in the pantry

00:07:10.750 --> 00:07:11.770
I've still not figured out.

00:07:11.770 --> 00:07:13.603
They should probably
be in the refrigerator.

00:07:13.603 --> 00:07:15.760
Apparently this is not
a perfected process,

00:07:15.760 --> 00:07:17.680
but that's OK.

00:07:17.680 --> 00:07:22.570
And if there is hot dogs
in the pantry, I'm all set.

00:07:22.570 --> 00:07:24.350
If there's not, I have
to go to the store.

00:07:24.350 --> 00:07:26.290
So there's a little
bit of a decision here.

00:07:26.290 --> 00:07:30.220
Here's another supplier,
which is the store.

00:07:30.220 --> 00:07:33.490
If I have everything I
need, I cook the hot dog,

00:07:33.490 --> 00:07:34.450
I put it in the bun.

00:07:34.450 --> 00:07:35.710
I give it to the kids.

00:07:35.710 --> 00:07:36.730
We're all set.

00:07:36.730 --> 00:07:39.100
There's a little bit of an
extra sort of tail end loop

00:07:39.100 --> 00:07:40.720
here, which is I
got to clean up.

00:07:40.720 --> 00:07:43.060
And if I'm smart about
it, I'll actually

00:07:43.060 --> 00:07:47.560
save myself some front
end work by putting

00:07:47.560 --> 00:07:50.350
hot dogs on the shopping
list if I used them all up.

00:07:50.350 --> 00:07:52.660
Not the greatest not
the greatest process

00:07:52.660 --> 00:07:55.210
map, but it's one
everyone can understand.

00:07:55.210 --> 00:07:57.160
You could probably
do better, and we're

00:07:57.160 --> 00:08:00.830
going to give you an
opportunity to do exactly that.

00:08:00.830 --> 00:08:03.650
We're going to do a little
bit more complicated process.

00:08:03.650 --> 00:08:06.340
It's not just kids
ordering from me.

00:08:06.340 --> 00:08:08.090
But it's not that
much more complicated,

00:08:08.090 --> 00:08:10.300
and it does, in fact,
involve fixing hot dogs.

00:08:10.300 --> 00:08:15.730
In your blue folder you have
a little story about Sasha

00:08:15.730 --> 00:08:18.970
and Andy's hot dog stand,
and the stuff in the front

00:08:18.970 --> 00:08:22.930
give you an introduction
to Sasha and Andy,

00:08:22.930 --> 00:08:24.910
who have a hot dog stand.

00:08:24.910 --> 00:08:28.180
And they're doing fine,
but they find that they

00:08:28.180 --> 00:08:29.350
are a little bit swamped.

00:08:29.350 --> 00:08:31.990
They have more customers
than they can deal with,

00:08:31.990 --> 00:08:35.150
and they want to
improve their process.

00:08:35.150 --> 00:08:37.429
So we're going to
help them do that.

00:08:37.429 --> 00:08:41.900
And so we're going to help them
do that with a direct exercise

00:08:41.900 --> 00:08:42.400
here.

00:08:42.400 --> 00:08:43.570
Read the sheet here.

00:08:43.570 --> 00:08:45.520
For you, their
process is actually

00:08:45.520 --> 00:08:46.840
already been broken down.

00:08:46.840 --> 00:08:49.900
If you were doing this with
your own process from start,

00:08:49.900 --> 00:08:52.150
you'd have to do the little
exercise of figuring out

00:08:52.150 --> 00:08:54.340
what are the steps,
what are the inputs

00:08:54.340 --> 00:08:55.900
and outputs to the steps.

00:08:55.900 --> 00:08:58.720
Don't even worry about the data
yet, just the first column.

00:08:58.720 --> 00:09:01.360
That's the steps that they take.

00:09:01.360 --> 00:09:03.790
That's been done for you,
and we're going to map this.

00:09:03.790 --> 00:09:08.620
So give you a second
to look at that.

00:09:08.620 --> 00:09:11.740
Think about the steps,
their inputs and outputs.

00:09:11.740 --> 00:09:14.440
And then we're going
to create a map using

00:09:14.440 --> 00:09:19.670
the post-it notes which are out
on the table with the sharpies.

00:09:19.670 --> 00:09:22.140
For each of the process
elements, make a post-it.

00:09:22.140 --> 00:09:24.300
And this is not supposed
to be complicated.

00:09:24.300 --> 00:09:27.650
The first one is,
let's see, take order.

00:09:27.650 --> 00:09:29.240
So let's make it easy.

00:09:29.240 --> 00:09:30.545
Take order.

00:09:34.387 --> 00:09:35.220
Who takes the order?

00:09:35.220 --> 00:09:36.290
Sasha takes the order.

00:09:36.290 --> 00:09:40.910
We could add that information,
or we could use color.

00:09:40.910 --> 00:09:44.973
Perhaps this color
implies Sasha.

00:09:44.973 --> 00:09:47.390
And we'll put that on our
thing, and we're using a sticky.

00:09:47.390 --> 00:09:47.890
Why?

00:09:50.460 --> 00:09:54.240
We can move it around
because a priori,

00:09:54.240 --> 00:09:56.760
we're not really sure how
these things should be arranged

00:09:56.760 --> 00:09:58.230
to make the most sense.

00:09:58.230 --> 00:10:00.770
Let's think about inputs and
outputs who gives the input?

00:10:03.660 --> 00:10:05.670
Customer, OK.

00:10:05.670 --> 00:10:08.858
So there's another one.

00:10:08.858 --> 00:10:10.650
So we might want to do
something like that.

00:10:10.650 --> 00:10:11.823
And you get the picture.

00:10:11.823 --> 00:10:13.740
We're not going to do
the whole thing for you.

00:10:13.740 --> 00:10:15.060
You're going to do it.

00:10:15.060 --> 00:10:15.930
Get the stickies.

00:10:15.930 --> 00:10:17.520
Arrange them on the board.

00:10:17.520 --> 00:10:19.980
Don't start drawing
lines yet because that

00:10:19.980 --> 00:10:23.940
would kind of ruin the point
of having the stickies there.

00:10:23.940 --> 00:10:27.360
When you think you have
everything puzzled out,

00:10:27.360 --> 00:10:30.970
there might be some other
details that are necessary.

00:10:30.970 --> 00:10:35.040
One of them is that there
might be waiting or inventory.

00:10:35.040 --> 00:10:38.640
There may be places
where the process waits.

00:10:38.640 --> 00:10:41.010
And the traditional symbol
for that is a triangle.

00:10:41.010 --> 00:10:43.500
We don't have any
triangle-shaped stickies,

00:10:43.500 --> 00:10:45.960
so we are going to use
something like this.

00:10:45.960 --> 00:10:48.700
Perhaps there is a
line of customers.

00:10:48.700 --> 00:10:52.048
So there's kind of an inventory
waiting box in front of them.

00:10:52.048 --> 00:10:52.590
I don't know.

00:10:52.590 --> 00:10:54.210
I'm making this
up as I go along.

00:10:54.210 --> 00:10:56.970
And perhaps a decision has
to be made at that point.

00:10:56.970 --> 00:10:59.370
Do we take the order or
tell them no, I'm sorry,

00:10:59.370 --> 00:11:01.320
we don't sell that?

00:11:01.320 --> 00:11:02.490
Decisions are diamonds.

00:11:02.490 --> 00:11:07.270
You can do a diamond by just
putting a square sideways.

00:11:07.270 --> 00:11:11.800
When all that is done, then
it's time to draw the lines.

00:11:11.800 --> 00:11:14.170
You can actually even
make that temporary

00:11:14.170 --> 00:11:17.230
and use stickies with arrows
on them, or use string.

00:11:17.230 --> 00:11:20.115
I've participated in
exercises where you do that.

00:11:20.115 --> 00:11:21.740
That's getting a
little bit too clever.

00:11:21.740 --> 00:11:22.780
It gets a bit messy.

00:11:22.780 --> 00:11:24.638
Best thing to do is
arrange everything

00:11:24.638 --> 00:11:25.930
on the board with the stickies.

00:11:25.930 --> 00:11:28.100
When you think you got
everything lined up,

00:11:28.100 --> 00:11:31.780
then draw lines to show
how the process is flowing.

00:11:31.780 --> 00:11:34.030
This is a speed exercise.

00:11:34.030 --> 00:11:37.160
You only have 10 minutes,
so get with your groups.

00:11:37.160 --> 00:11:41.980
Here are the basic mapping
symbols, triangle, rectangle,

00:11:41.980 --> 00:11:43.060
diamond.

00:11:43.060 --> 00:11:44.290
Don't worry about issues yet.

00:11:44.290 --> 00:11:45.490
We're going to get to that.

00:11:45.490 --> 00:11:49.150
Map out this process.

00:11:49.150 --> 00:12:09.160
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:12:09.160 --> 00:12:11.120
HUGH MCMANUS: So time's up.

00:12:11.120 --> 00:12:12.640
I think everybody's
got something

00:12:12.640 --> 00:12:14.620
that approximates a map here.

00:12:14.620 --> 00:12:16.450
And don't worry,
you'll get that chance

00:12:16.450 --> 00:12:20.420
to play with it more
in the near future.

00:12:20.420 --> 00:12:21.820
So let's see what we have.

00:12:21.820 --> 00:12:23.860
Let's have the
folks in the back,

00:12:23.860 --> 00:12:25.970
who have a map that
looks kind of different,

00:12:25.970 --> 00:12:28.490
let us know what they have.

00:12:28.490 --> 00:12:31.810
AUDIENCE: So we had the
[INAUDIBLE] colors as well,

00:12:31.810 --> 00:12:36.830
and it starts at the upper
left and goes down here.

00:12:36.830 --> 00:12:39.590
We don't actually
have the process line,

00:12:39.590 --> 00:12:45.250
but essentially the time
next to each post-it

00:12:45.250 --> 00:12:49.210
referred to how long that
is suggested to take.

00:12:49.210 --> 00:12:54.620
And then we have this
loop-interlook process here

00:12:54.620 --> 00:12:58.280
where Andy will need to prepare
the hot dog, and potentially

00:12:58.280 --> 00:12:59.630
multiple hot dogs.

00:12:59.630 --> 00:13:02.810
And coming up here,
Sasha checking the order

00:13:02.810 --> 00:13:07.615
and completing that process,
as well as ending with

00:13:07.615 --> 00:13:11.905
a 10-minute-per-hour
makes sense.

00:13:11.905 --> 00:13:13.280
HUGH MCMANUS: And
you've got sort

00:13:13.280 --> 00:13:15.540
of a different
physical arrangement.

00:13:15.540 --> 00:13:17.340
Comes down and
then back up again,

00:13:17.340 --> 00:13:20.060
which is sort of enforced by
the geometry of that board.

00:13:20.060 --> 00:13:23.420
So that's fine.

00:13:23.420 --> 00:13:25.732
And I guess because maybe
you didn't have time

00:13:25.732 --> 00:13:28.190
to finish with the lines, it's
a little bit less clear kind

00:13:28.190 --> 00:13:29.480
of what the rework is.

00:13:29.480 --> 00:13:32.240
It looks a little more linear.

00:13:32.240 --> 00:13:33.047
That's fine.

00:13:33.047 --> 00:13:34.880
And I don't think we're
going to go through.

00:13:34.880 --> 00:13:37.880
It looks like everybody
else also did a nice job.

00:13:37.880 --> 00:13:40.490
The point, though, is not to
go through each individual one

00:13:40.490 --> 00:13:41.800
and give you a grade.

00:13:41.800 --> 00:13:45.290
The point actually is that
I think all of these maps

00:13:45.290 --> 00:13:47.450
are successful in
visually representing

00:13:47.450 --> 00:13:50.780
the process and some of
its difficulties, the fact

00:13:50.780 --> 00:13:54.530
that it is fairly long, that
it has reworks and decisions,

00:13:54.530 --> 00:13:57.200
that it has weights and times.

00:13:57.200 --> 00:13:58.220
Those are all captured.

00:13:58.220 --> 00:14:02.420
And there's no real right
answer because that's

00:14:02.420 --> 00:14:05.480
the point of our next slide.

00:14:05.480 --> 00:14:07.580
It's a 2D visualization.

00:14:07.580 --> 00:14:11.450
It's something that's actually
taking place in 3D space.

00:14:11.450 --> 00:14:13.610
Plus there's time issues.

00:14:13.610 --> 00:14:16.820
There's issues of
these processes

00:14:16.820 --> 00:14:18.290
that are not on the main loop.

00:14:18.290 --> 00:14:20.210
You can't basically
get everything

00:14:20.210 --> 00:14:21.620
into a two-dimensional map.

00:14:21.620 --> 00:14:22.880
You do the best you can.

00:14:22.880 --> 00:14:27.490
You use it as a way of
communicating the process.

00:14:27.490 --> 00:14:30.680
So capturing and communicating
the key features of the process

00:14:30.680 --> 00:14:32.540
is what you want to do.

00:14:32.540 --> 00:14:34.400
One thing that you do
have to be careful of,

00:14:34.400 --> 00:14:37.580
and this exercise is actually
fairly carefully designed

00:14:37.580 --> 00:14:39.470
this way, you have to capture--

00:14:39.470 --> 00:14:41.840
I actually shouldn't say
avoid unneeded details.

00:14:41.840 --> 00:14:44.240
You have to capture the
right level of detail.

00:14:44.240 --> 00:14:46.940
If we just said,
make the hot dog,

00:14:46.940 --> 00:14:49.670
we'd miss all of this
interesting stuff.

00:14:49.670 --> 00:14:52.768
On the other hand, if we went
through--and some people did,

00:14:52.768 --> 00:14:55.310
and that's OK because I didn't
tell you not to-- went through

00:14:55.310 --> 00:14:58.280
the individual, OK, take the
order, chat with the customer,

00:14:58.280 --> 00:14:59.930
take the money.

00:14:59.930 --> 00:15:05.135
At some level of detail we
might actually want to do that.

00:15:05.135 --> 00:15:07.010
At the level of detail
of this whole process,

00:15:07.010 --> 00:15:09.200
if we get into those
individual things,

00:15:09.200 --> 00:15:10.910
it gets too complicated.

00:15:10.910 --> 00:15:16.190
so most folks did capture that
level of detail about right.

00:15:20.870 --> 00:15:23.930
So I think we've all
succeeded in doing

00:15:23.930 --> 00:15:25.460
the key thing,
which is capturing

00:15:25.460 --> 00:15:27.615
the features of the process.

00:15:27.615 --> 00:15:29.240
We're going to come
back to these maps.

00:15:29.240 --> 00:15:32.900
But for now, that's
it for processes.

00:15:32.900 --> 00:15:35.420
Like I said, if there's one
thing you take away from here,

00:15:35.420 --> 00:15:37.880
it's thinking about
work as processes

00:15:37.880 --> 00:15:41.150
because once you think of
something as a process,

00:15:41.150 --> 00:15:44.990
you can understand and improve
it, often fairly intuitively.

00:15:44.990 --> 00:15:49.970
Often it really is application
of common sense to the process

00:15:49.970 --> 00:15:52.890
to make it better.

00:15:52.890 --> 00:15:54.870
So a little bit of
a transition now.

00:15:54.870 --> 00:16:00.190
We're going to get into the
five Lean thinking fundamentals.

00:16:00.190 --> 00:16:03.240
Earl introduced you a little
earlier to the origins of Lean,

00:16:03.240 --> 00:16:08.100
how it came out of a study
of Japanese practices

00:16:08.100 --> 00:16:10.020
by Jim Womack and his team.

00:16:10.020 --> 00:16:13.930
And Womack and Jones
wrote a book in 1995,

00:16:13.930 --> 00:16:17.140
where they basically
took the base, the ideas,

00:16:17.140 --> 00:16:20.430
the concepts of
the Japanese system

00:16:20.430 --> 00:16:25.970
and captured them not
so much as a system,

00:16:25.970 --> 00:16:31.530
but as a way of transforming
existing processes into better

00:16:31.530 --> 00:16:32.030
ones.

00:16:32.030 --> 00:16:33.680
They said, let's
take these principles

00:16:33.680 --> 00:16:35.690
and figure out how
they can be used

00:16:35.690 --> 00:16:38.840
to take existing processes,
which are maybe not so great,

00:16:38.840 --> 00:16:40.970
and transform them
into better ones.

00:16:40.970 --> 00:16:43.340
And that's kind of
the essence of Lean

00:16:43.340 --> 00:16:46.940
as practiced in North
America and Europe, at least.

00:16:46.940 --> 00:16:47.690
And here they are.

00:16:47.690 --> 00:16:51.110
Here are the
fundamental principles.

00:16:51.110 --> 00:16:52.850
First of all, specify value.

00:16:52.850 --> 00:16:55.960
Understand what we want to
accomplish because if we don't

00:16:55.960 --> 00:16:59.830
do that, we can't
really think clearly

00:16:59.830 --> 00:17:01.640
about any of the other steps.

00:17:01.640 --> 00:17:05.930
So what is the value
of our hot dog stand?

00:17:05.930 --> 00:17:08.150
What is the value
of a hot dog stand?

00:17:08.150 --> 00:17:09.230
Hot dogs, right?

00:17:09.230 --> 00:17:14.480
Hot dogs for customers, warm,
safe, no diseases or bugs.

00:17:14.480 --> 00:17:17.750
You can think of a couple
of the quality issues.

00:17:17.750 --> 00:17:19.530
You can think of
some nuance to it.

00:17:19.530 --> 00:17:21.619
But basically, we
want to make hot dogs.

00:17:21.619 --> 00:17:23.660
Identify the value stream.

00:17:23.660 --> 00:17:25.310
We've sort of done that.

00:17:25.310 --> 00:17:31.630
If we think about the process
and take a process map,

00:17:31.630 --> 00:17:34.370
but a rather specific
kind of process map, which

00:17:34.370 --> 00:17:37.820
is a process map that
follows the value

00:17:37.820 --> 00:17:40.400
added product
through the process,

00:17:40.400 --> 00:17:45.050
and then think about how
value is added to that product

00:17:45.050 --> 00:17:48.260
as it moves through the process,
that's a value stream map.

00:17:48.260 --> 00:17:49.550
We're pretty close on this.

00:17:49.550 --> 00:17:51.380
We figured out the
value is the hot dog,

00:17:51.380 --> 00:17:53.240
and we're following the
hot dog pretty much.

00:17:53.240 --> 00:17:56.820
We're following a hot
dog order through there.

00:17:56.820 --> 00:18:00.200
So all of ours are
approaching value stream.

00:18:00.200 --> 00:18:01.730
Not all process maps are.

00:18:01.730 --> 00:18:04.130
We could have followed
Sasha around, right?

00:18:04.130 --> 00:18:06.000
What does that person do?

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:07.670
That's not a value stream map.

00:18:07.670 --> 00:18:08.690
It's a process map.

00:18:08.690 --> 00:18:10.820
It's following that
person's work process.

00:18:10.820 --> 00:18:13.850
But value stream map
follows the product,

00:18:13.850 --> 00:18:15.290
the value added product.

00:18:15.290 --> 00:18:16.790
Make value flow.

00:18:16.790 --> 00:18:18.200
Saw a couple of maps earlier.

00:18:18.200 --> 00:18:20.000
There was that engineering map.

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:22.010
Didn't look like a lot
of flow in that map.

00:18:22.010 --> 00:18:24.870
The lines are all
over the place.

00:18:24.870 --> 00:18:26.420
The heart attack map was better.

00:18:26.420 --> 00:18:29.660
At least there was
some coherent patient

00:18:29.660 --> 00:18:32.700
comes in to patient is
resolved, in some way.

00:18:32.700 --> 00:18:35.300
So there was a potential
there for flow, at least.

00:18:35.300 --> 00:18:37.205
But Earl was saying
that in the old state,

00:18:37.205 --> 00:18:39.080
it wasn't really being
achieved because there

00:18:39.080 --> 00:18:40.520
was too many steps.

00:18:40.520 --> 00:18:42.030
It was too slow.

00:18:42.030 --> 00:18:44.990
So what we would like
to do is have value flow

00:18:44.990 --> 00:18:47.930
through the value stream
as continuously as

00:18:47.930 --> 00:18:50.960
possible, not necessarily as
fast as possible, a low speed.

00:18:50.960 --> 00:18:53.840
Usually processes
are too slow, so it's

00:18:53.840 --> 00:18:56.570
reasonable to say we would
like it to flow quickly

00:18:56.570 --> 00:18:58.130
through the process.

00:18:58.130 --> 00:19:01.093
Then we get a little
bit more sophisticated,

00:19:01.093 --> 00:19:02.510
and by the end of
the class, we'll

00:19:02.510 --> 00:19:04.850
get to what this concept means.

00:19:04.850 --> 00:19:07.160
It may not be
intuitive right away.

00:19:07.160 --> 00:19:09.950
If we have a system
that flows and creates

00:19:09.950 --> 00:19:12.590
value for the customer,
there's the potential

00:19:12.590 --> 00:19:16.820
that we can allow the customers
to pull value from that system.

00:19:16.820 --> 00:19:19.340
Like Lean, that's a
slightly fraught word.

00:19:19.340 --> 00:19:20.990
What does that mean,
especially when

00:19:20.990 --> 00:19:23.450
we're pulling on something
that flows or pulling on water?

00:19:23.450 --> 00:19:25.742
I don't know, the metaphor's
getting kind of messed up.

00:19:25.742 --> 00:19:30.890
But the idea here is that
essentially if the system flows

00:19:30.890 --> 00:19:33.380
continuously and creates
value, from the customer's

00:19:33.380 --> 00:19:36.170
point of view, when they
want something, they get it.

00:19:36.170 --> 00:19:38.900
They can come up to the hot dog
stand, say, I want a hot dog.

00:19:38.900 --> 00:19:39.980
The hot dog comes.

00:19:39.980 --> 00:19:42.140
They're happy.

00:19:42.140 --> 00:19:47.810
And this act of satisfying
the customer actually

00:19:47.810 --> 00:19:52.100
controls the process all the
way back to the lowest levels.

00:19:52.100 --> 00:19:54.110
The customer gets their hot dog.

00:19:54.110 --> 00:19:56.123
We essentially
have a process that

00:19:56.123 --> 00:19:58.040
doesn't require a whole
lot of decision making

00:19:58.040 --> 00:20:01.460
that isn't complicated,
that flows, that creates

00:20:01.460 --> 00:20:05.000
the hot dogs, that orders the
buns, that cleans up the grill,

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:05.810
whatever.

00:20:05.810 --> 00:20:10.190
The whole system is set up
so that the customer desire

00:20:10.190 --> 00:20:14.600
activates the system to satisfy
that desire in a way that's

00:20:14.600 --> 00:20:17.510
continuous and easy
and creates value

00:20:17.510 --> 00:20:19.610
with the minimum of waste.

00:20:19.610 --> 00:20:21.260
And finally,
pursuing perfection.

00:20:21.260 --> 00:20:23.150
If we can do all
of this, we're not

00:20:23.150 --> 00:20:25.730
done because we can
always do better.

00:20:25.730 --> 00:20:29.660
Earl mentioned the F18,
how they identified them

00:20:29.660 --> 00:20:31.747
as a Lean enterprise.

00:20:31.747 --> 00:20:33.830
And the first thing they
said is, that's not true.

00:20:33.830 --> 00:20:35.570
We have so much more to do.

00:20:35.570 --> 00:20:37.130
Right attitude.

00:20:37.130 --> 00:20:39.500
They knew that they
weren't perfect.

00:20:39.500 --> 00:20:41.660
An external observer
said you're pretty good.

00:20:41.660 --> 00:20:43.400
But they knew that
they weren't perfect.

00:20:43.400 --> 00:20:46.580
They were, in fact,
pursuing perfection.

00:20:46.580 --> 00:20:48.900
So this is a continuous process.

00:20:48.900 --> 00:20:49.400
All right.

00:20:49.400 --> 00:20:52.220
So we're going to spend
the rest of both this unit,

00:20:52.220 --> 00:20:54.530
and then after lunch, the
second unit, essentially

00:20:54.530 --> 00:20:57.530
walking through these
concepts, going a little deeper

00:20:57.530 --> 00:21:00.830
and also giving you some tools
on each one of these levels.

00:21:00.830 --> 00:21:03.750
First thing we're going
to talk about is value.

00:21:03.750 --> 00:21:06.560
This one is fraught.

00:21:06.560 --> 00:21:10.510
It's fairly easy
to define value--

00:21:10.510 --> 00:21:11.112
not always.

00:21:11.112 --> 00:21:12.820
You have to be a little
bit careful- But?

00:21:12.820 --> 00:21:14.320
It's fairly easy
to define the value

00:21:14.320 --> 00:21:16.880
of the output of a process.

00:21:16.880 --> 00:21:17.850
We want hot dogs.

00:21:17.850 --> 00:21:19.220
That's our value.

00:21:19.220 --> 00:21:21.350
When we start looking
in more detail,

00:21:21.350 --> 00:21:24.410
what's the value of the
individual process steps?

00:21:24.410 --> 00:21:28.100
Is cooking the hot dog valuable?

00:21:28.100 --> 00:21:31.270
I hope so, assuming
you want it cooked.

00:21:31.270 --> 00:21:37.730
But is cleaning
the grill valuable?

00:21:37.730 --> 00:21:38.927
Maybe.

00:21:38.927 --> 00:21:40.760
We have to think about
that a little harder.

00:21:40.760 --> 00:21:45.210
And in a real workplace,
this can get very difficult,

00:21:45.210 --> 00:21:48.740
especially if you
start attaching

00:21:48.740 --> 00:21:53.170
personal self-worth issues.

00:21:53.170 --> 00:21:55.455
If you're told you
are non-value added,

00:21:55.455 --> 00:21:56.830
what does that do
to your morale?

00:22:00.040 --> 00:22:03.050
And it's not just
a morale issue.

00:22:03.050 --> 00:22:04.330
It's also a motivation issue.

00:22:04.330 --> 00:22:10.030
When we first started applying
Lean to product development

00:22:10.030 --> 00:22:14.800
activities, we got things
completely up and down

00:22:14.800 --> 00:22:20.440
the scale from people arguing
that their work was valuable

00:22:20.440 --> 00:22:23.800
because they knew it was without
really any context to what it

00:22:23.800 --> 00:22:26.080
did for the customer, all
the way to the other side,

00:22:26.080 --> 00:22:27.730
where we had some
Lean experts come in

00:22:27.730 --> 00:22:31.930
and say, well, analysis isn't
valuable because it doesn't add

00:22:31.930 --> 00:22:35.350
anything directly to the
customer, which, as an analyst,

00:22:35.350 --> 00:22:37.120
I sort of had problems with.

00:22:37.120 --> 00:22:40.090
It took me a while to figure
out exactly what the problem was

00:22:40.090 --> 00:22:40.930
with that.

00:22:40.930 --> 00:22:46.840
But people that were too
eager to essentially say

00:22:46.840 --> 00:22:49.870
that activities, and
by implication, people

00:22:49.870 --> 00:22:50.950
were non-value added.

00:22:50.950 --> 00:22:53.310
The point is that you
have to think about it.

00:22:53.310 --> 00:22:55.600
So there's some guides on here.

00:22:55.600 --> 00:22:59.020
We can think about value as
like cooking the hot dog, things

00:22:59.020 --> 00:23:04.480
that directly transform material
or information in the direction

00:23:04.480 --> 00:23:09.220
of the customer's desire and
done correctly, no mistakes.

00:23:09.220 --> 00:23:14.690
That's unambiguously valuable.

00:23:14.690 --> 00:23:18.310
The other end's kind of easy to
think about, too, pure waste.

00:23:18.310 --> 00:23:20.660
Consumes resources
but creates no value.

00:23:20.660 --> 00:23:22.180
So waiting.

00:23:22.180 --> 00:23:24.520
Inventory, stuff that's
just sitting around.

00:23:24.520 --> 00:23:26.770
Mistakes.

00:23:26.770 --> 00:23:31.150
Reworking things in a
creative sense can be good.

00:23:31.150 --> 00:23:34.300
But if it's because you're
fixing a mistake, no value

00:23:34.300 --> 00:23:35.560
there.

00:23:35.560 --> 00:23:36.888
Things like that.

00:23:36.888 --> 00:23:38.680
And then in the middle,
there may be things

00:23:38.680 --> 00:23:42.950
that we know don't really add
value but we simply have to do.

00:23:42.950 --> 00:23:44.860
There may be setup
and tear down issues

00:23:44.860 --> 00:23:46.510
with our current technologies.

00:23:46.510 --> 00:23:49.930
There may be the necessity
to do project coordination.

00:23:49.930 --> 00:23:53.720
We may have to satisfy
regulations or laws.

00:23:53.720 --> 00:23:57.780
So there may be things
that we got to do.

00:23:57.780 --> 00:23:59.508
Like I said, t the
individual task level,

00:23:59.508 --> 00:24:01.050
that's not necessarily
an easy thing,

00:24:01.050 --> 00:24:03.250
and here's a great example.

00:24:03.250 --> 00:24:04.780
Does inspection add value?

00:24:04.780 --> 00:24:07.200
A couple of little
brainteasers here.

00:24:07.200 --> 00:24:09.490
Inspect those.

00:24:09.490 --> 00:24:13.230
Everybody got them, maybe?

