On the other hand, you
might have to do that.

00:25:14.610 --> 00:25:16.242
If something is
super safety critical

00:25:16.242 --> 00:25:18.450
and it's just really hard
to do right the first time,

00:25:18.450 --> 00:25:19.950
you might have to inspect it.

00:25:19.950 --> 00:25:23.580
Also, continuous inspection
of the work process

00:25:23.580 --> 00:25:25.860
is known to be quite valuable.

00:25:25.860 --> 00:25:28.050
Inspecting in quality
at the end of something

00:25:28.050 --> 00:25:31.080
that should go right the
first time, probably not.

00:25:31.080 --> 00:25:33.600
And unfortunately a lot
of traditional, especially

00:25:33.600 --> 00:25:36.180
manufacturing-type processes
lean on that a little too

00:25:36.180 --> 00:25:37.020
heavily.

00:25:37.020 --> 00:25:41.700
So context dependent,
an interesting case

00:25:41.700 --> 00:25:44.100
where you have to be
careful that you don't

00:25:44.100 --> 00:25:46.810
assume something either way.

00:25:46.810 --> 00:25:48.060
Inspection is non-value added.

00:25:48.060 --> 00:25:49.380
No, no, no, it's
super safety critical.

00:25:49.380 --> 00:25:49.920
We got to do it.

00:25:49.920 --> 00:25:51.545
I don't want to fly
in an airplane that

00:25:51.545 --> 00:25:53.490
hasn't been inspected.

00:25:53.490 --> 00:25:56.100
But inspecting something that's
coming off a line that you're

00:25:56.100 --> 00:25:59.190
making a million of, given
that you know inspection

00:25:59.190 --> 00:26:02.880
doesn't work very well as a
quality method, not so good.

00:26:02.880 --> 00:26:04.478
So that's value.

00:26:04.478 --> 00:26:06.270
We're going to do a
little exercise in that

00:26:06.270 --> 00:26:09.450
before the day is over,
before this class is over.

00:26:09.450 --> 00:26:12.030
Identifying value stream.

00:26:12.030 --> 00:26:13.470
What is the value stream?

00:26:13.470 --> 00:26:17.580
It's the end- to-end
activities that

00:26:17.580 --> 00:26:19.020
take place to deliver value.

00:26:19.020 --> 00:26:22.230
Said this already against
that first slide, starting

00:26:22.230 --> 00:26:24.730
with the raw material or
the initial information,

00:26:24.730 --> 00:26:26.700
ending with the
customer, or user.

00:26:26.700 --> 00:26:28.890
From the beginning to
the end, the material,

00:26:28.890 --> 00:26:33.960
the product flows is often a
backwards flow of information.

00:26:33.960 --> 00:26:37.410
Customer needs, schedules,
inventory information,

00:26:37.410 --> 00:26:38.280
et cetera.

00:26:38.280 --> 00:26:41.610
So is the main flow of the
value from raw material

00:26:41.610 --> 00:26:45.630
or raw information to something
the customer wants, often

00:26:45.630 --> 00:26:49.820
a backwards flow of information.

00:26:49.820 --> 00:26:52.100
What moves in a value stream?

00:26:52.100 --> 00:26:53.390
Manufacturing, it's easy.

00:26:53.390 --> 00:26:55.160
Stuff.

00:26:55.160 --> 00:26:58.420
In design and
services, less easy.

00:26:58.420 --> 00:27:01.410
Some kind of information flows.

00:27:01.410 --> 00:27:02.410
I call it the help line.

00:27:02.410 --> 00:27:03.730
I have a question.

00:27:03.730 --> 00:27:04.960
I want an answer.

00:27:04.960 --> 00:27:06.970
It's all information.

00:27:06.970 --> 00:27:07.758
It's not physical.

00:27:07.758 --> 00:27:10.300
It makes it a little bit harder
to track, a little bit harder

00:27:10.300 --> 00:27:11.320
to think about.

00:27:11.320 --> 00:27:13.210
But there is a
flow of information

00:27:13.210 --> 00:27:15.220
that is satisfying the customer.

00:27:15.220 --> 00:27:18.670
In human services, medical,
for example, it may be people.

00:27:18.670 --> 00:27:22.730
It may be the actual customer
flowing through the system.

00:27:22.730 --> 00:27:24.220
And that could be in medicine.

00:27:24.220 --> 00:27:28.330
It could also be great
Lean company, Disneyland.

00:27:28.330 --> 00:27:31.450
They process people
and make them happy.

00:27:31.450 --> 00:27:34.780
But they think of it
very much as a process.

00:27:34.780 --> 00:27:37.690
So there's a flow of people
coming in sad and grumpy

00:27:37.690 --> 00:27:44.080
and going out sad, grumpy, and
hot and poor, at least in my--

00:27:44.080 --> 00:27:45.023
no, I joke.

00:27:45.023 --> 00:27:45.940
They have a good time.

00:27:45.940 --> 00:27:50.880
And the process is
set up so they do.

00:27:50.880 --> 00:27:54.150
So thinking about value streams
the definition of the value

00:27:54.150 --> 00:27:56.640
stream is the set
of activities that

00:27:56.640 --> 00:28:00.820
adds value to the work product
to satisfy the customer.

00:28:00.820 --> 00:28:03.960
So the first order analysis
of the value stream

00:28:03.960 --> 00:28:07.740
is to look for things that
don't do that, look for waste.

00:28:07.740 --> 00:28:10.290
This is called waste hunting,
and it's actually a lot of fun

00:28:10.290 --> 00:28:11.820
because it's easy.

00:28:11.820 --> 00:28:14.160
Most processes, once
you've defined them,

00:28:14.160 --> 00:28:16.910
it's very easy to
find wasteful steps.

00:28:16.910 --> 00:28:18.660
May be a little harder
to get rid of them,

00:28:18.660 --> 00:28:20.960
but it's really
easy to find them.

00:28:20.960 --> 00:28:23.280
And waste comes in a couple
of different flavors.

00:28:23.280 --> 00:28:25.340
We're actually going
to be talking mostly

00:28:25.340 --> 00:28:28.010
about muda, about
just looking at stuff

00:28:28.010 --> 00:28:31.160
that doesn't add value.

00:28:31.160 --> 00:28:36.200
So cleaning the grill or
waiting or throwing away

00:28:36.200 --> 00:28:39.560
the unused hot dogs at the
end of the day, or stuff that

00:28:39.560 --> 00:28:41.603
just is clearly not valuable.

00:28:41.603 --> 00:28:43.770
Something to keep in the
back of your mind, though--

00:28:43.770 --> 00:28:46.370
and we'll come
back to this later,

00:28:46.370 --> 00:28:48.710
especially the
health care folks,

00:28:48.710 --> 00:28:52.810
you're going to get a good
dose of this tomorrow--

00:28:52.810 --> 00:28:56.500
are issues that can cause muda.

00:28:56.500 --> 00:28:59.470
And there's some Japanese
words associated with this that

00:28:59.470 --> 00:29:01.490
don't have good translations.

00:29:01.490 --> 00:29:05.500
So we like to use the
Japanese muri, overburden

00:29:05.500 --> 00:29:08.350
or unreasonableness.

00:29:08.350 --> 00:29:11.950
Essentially, there's
somebody in the process that

00:29:11.950 --> 00:29:14.700
too much is being asked of.

00:29:14.700 --> 00:29:18.108
Telling them to work harder
doesn't do very much good.

00:29:18.108 --> 00:29:18.900
This can be people.

00:29:18.900 --> 00:29:20.550
It can be machines.

00:29:20.550 --> 00:29:22.410
We've got to run
this machine 24/7.

00:29:22.410 --> 00:29:26.090
How good is that process?

00:29:26.090 --> 00:29:27.347
How long is it going to work?

00:29:27.347 --> 00:29:29.180
It's going to work until
the machine breaks,

00:29:29.180 --> 00:29:31.170
and then it's not going
to work at all anymore.

00:29:31.170 --> 00:29:35.420
So being unreasonable,
overburdening things

00:29:35.420 --> 00:29:39.260
tends to spawn muda waste.

00:29:39.260 --> 00:29:44.930
Even more dynamic as is mura,
unevenness, instability.

00:29:44.930 --> 00:29:49.310
Again, there aren't
particularly good translations.

00:29:49.310 --> 00:29:52.610
But the idea here is that
if the process is uneven,

00:29:52.610 --> 00:29:56.480
if it's irregular or
fluctuating, it can't flow.

00:29:56.480 --> 00:30:00.320
Again, our metaphor there, our
sort of fluid flow metaphor,

00:30:00.320 --> 00:30:04.040
if the stream is turbulent,
if it has back flows, if it

00:30:04.040 --> 00:30:06.050
has backwaters where
it's not flowing,

00:30:06.050 --> 00:30:10.550
it has fast parts where it
is flowing, if it's uneven,

00:30:10.550 --> 00:30:13.400
it's not going to be
an efficient process.

00:30:13.400 --> 00:30:16.970
And so these are
also kinds of wastes

00:30:16.970 --> 00:30:20.510
that one should look for.

00:30:20.510 --> 00:30:24.560
And often, these are the
root causes of the musa,

00:30:24.560 --> 00:30:26.030
of the obvious waste.

00:30:26.030 --> 00:30:29.660
Here are seven or eight mudas.

00:30:29.660 --> 00:30:33.500
These are sort of classic,
right out of Toyota and Womack.

00:30:33.500 --> 00:30:35.250
There are lots of
lists like this.

00:30:35.250 --> 00:30:37.830
In fact, most fields-- if you're
in health care, engineering,

00:30:37.830 --> 00:30:40.230
whatever, you look
up the latest book,

00:30:40.230 --> 00:30:41.480
they'll have a list like this.

00:30:41.480 --> 00:30:43.790
It won't be the same because
everybody likes to make up

00:30:43.790 --> 00:30:46.170
lists for their own field.

00:30:46.170 --> 00:30:47.930
That's fine, actually.

00:30:47.930 --> 00:30:49.790
These actually are
kind of fundamental.

00:30:49.790 --> 00:30:52.370
You can translate these
into almost any field.

00:30:52.370 --> 00:30:55.160
But if you want to make up
your own, that's good, too.

00:30:55.160 --> 00:30:57.410
The whole point
is to categorize.

00:30:57.410 --> 00:30:59.750
Categorizing waste
makes it easier to spot.

00:30:59.750 --> 00:31:02.677
So things like waiting.

00:31:02.677 --> 00:31:03.760
That's pretty fundamental.

00:31:03.760 --> 00:31:06.340
Stuff that's not moving,
people that aren't working,

00:31:06.340 --> 00:31:08.290
it's a waste.

00:31:08.290 --> 00:31:10.000
Moving stuff around.

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:13.870
Moving employees or moving
the material or information.

00:31:13.870 --> 00:31:16.900
This is essentially movement
of the value added stuff.

00:31:16.900 --> 00:31:18.970
This is movement
of the resources,

00:31:18.970 --> 00:31:22.220
the employees, and the stuff
necessary to do the work.

00:31:22.220 --> 00:31:24.210
Either of those is a waste.

00:31:24.210 --> 00:31:27.400
If your stuff is moving around,
it's not being worked on,

00:31:27.400 --> 00:31:29.260
and that costs
money or something.

00:31:29.260 --> 00:31:30.220
It costs people's time.

00:31:30.220 --> 00:31:33.210
It costs money to
move around inventory.

00:31:33.210 --> 00:31:34.188
Stuff that's sitting.

00:31:34.188 --> 00:31:35.730
It's kind of the
converse of waiting.

00:31:35.730 --> 00:31:39.050
People are waiting,
stuff is waiting.

00:31:39.050 --> 00:31:40.640
Producing too much.

00:31:40.640 --> 00:31:43.100
It's efficient to produce
large batches of things.

00:31:43.100 --> 00:31:45.750
That's still true even
in our Lean world.

00:31:45.750 --> 00:31:49.070
However, if you don't
need them, it's a waste.

00:31:49.070 --> 00:31:52.520
It's tempting, in Earl's
analogy, to buy what's on sale,

00:31:52.520 --> 00:31:56.030
but if it goes bad, that's
a waste, having too much.

00:31:56.030 --> 00:31:58.220
Defects, always bad.

00:31:58.220 --> 00:32:01.910
Doing more work than you need
to affect the transformation.

00:32:01.910 --> 00:32:05.200
Engineers are great at that.

00:32:05.200 --> 00:32:08.710
There's some question about
whether our health care system

00:32:08.710 --> 00:32:10.900
over processes these things.

00:32:10.900 --> 00:32:15.740
That's a controversy, but all
of these things don't add value.

00:32:15.740 --> 00:32:20.860
And they're fairly easy to spot.

00:32:20.860 --> 00:32:23.590
Unused employee
creativity is often

00:32:23.590 --> 00:32:25.810
added as the eighth waste.

00:32:25.810 --> 00:32:27.620
Essentially, it's
missed opportunities.

00:32:27.620 --> 00:32:29.290
It may be just missed work.

00:32:29.290 --> 00:32:31.960
But if they're just not
working, that's waiting.

00:32:31.960 --> 00:32:34.400
But if they're working
at a sort of mental level

00:32:34.400 --> 00:32:36.940
that's beneath them, if
you're losing opportunities

00:32:36.940 --> 00:32:39.520
to take advantage of the
employee's creativity

00:32:39.520 --> 00:32:43.700
and capability, that,
too, is a waste.

00:32:43.700 --> 00:32:46.880
Here's a really simple example
of unnecessary movement

00:32:46.880 --> 00:32:48.770
from the health care world.

00:32:48.770 --> 00:32:50.470
This is called a
spaghetti chart.

00:32:50.470 --> 00:32:52.118
It's actually a kind
of process chart.

00:32:52.118 --> 00:32:53.285
It's not a value stream map.

00:32:53.285 --> 00:32:55.240
It's completely different.

00:32:55.240 --> 00:32:59.200
You have a physical layout
that's a hospital floor.

00:32:59.200 --> 00:33:00.820
And you trace something.

00:33:00.820 --> 00:33:02.180
It could be the patient.

00:33:02.180 --> 00:33:03.100
It could be the nurse.

00:33:03.100 --> 00:33:05.830
In this case it's the
nurse doing their work.

00:33:05.830 --> 00:33:10.980
And this nurse is
all over the place

00:33:10.980 --> 00:33:12.730
just because things
are badly arranged.

00:33:12.730 --> 00:33:15.280
To get the work
done, she actually

00:33:15.280 --> 00:33:21.098
ends up walking 1250 feet
to do something trivial.

00:33:21.098 --> 00:33:23.640
Hopefully the patient is going
from the elevator to the room,

00:33:23.640 --> 00:33:25.890
but the nurse, to get
the patient checked in,

00:33:25.890 --> 00:33:28.270
has to run all over the
place to do their job.

00:33:28.270 --> 00:33:34.430
So it's a great visual way
of finding waste of movement.

00:33:34.430 --> 00:33:38.480
And here's some tools at this
value stream level to help.

00:33:38.480 --> 00:33:39.950
One of them is called kitting.

00:33:39.950 --> 00:33:43.790
This is kind of the
active version of 5S.

00:33:43.790 --> 00:33:47.310
If we need to move materials
to the place of work,

00:33:47.310 --> 00:33:49.190
why don't we move
them laid out the way

00:33:49.190 --> 00:33:52.150
they're going to be used?

00:33:52.150 --> 00:33:54.348
So here's a aerospace example.

00:33:54.348 --> 00:33:56.890
We had a beautiful picture that
we didn't have copyright for,

00:33:56.890 --> 00:33:58.730
so now we have a bad diagram.

00:33:58.730 --> 00:34:01.740
But if you have a complicated
mechanical assembly that

00:34:01.740 --> 00:34:03.790
uses lots of tubes
and wires, why not

00:34:03.790 --> 00:34:06.423
just deliver all the tubes
and wires you need in a box

00:34:06.423 --> 00:34:08.590
where they're laid out nice
and easy for the workers

00:34:08.590 --> 00:34:09.420
to get them?

00:34:09.420 --> 00:34:10.929
Likewise for a
medical procedure,

00:34:10.929 --> 00:34:17.139
having everything laid out nice
and neat is a good practice.

00:34:17.139 --> 00:34:18.010
Not new, right?

00:34:18.010 --> 00:34:20.800
I mean, a good OR
doctor is going

00:34:20.800 --> 00:34:22.989
to have a tray that
looks like that.

00:34:22.989 --> 00:34:24.699
But why isn't that
standard practice?

00:34:24.699 --> 00:34:27.250
Why isn't that just
done everywhere?

00:34:27.250 --> 00:34:28.510
Mistake proofing.

00:34:28.510 --> 00:34:31.780
Mistakes in a process are waste.

00:34:31.780 --> 00:34:36.610
And relying on people to
fix mistakes is dicey.

00:34:36.610 --> 00:34:39.221
People are good at some things,
but not so good at others.

00:34:39.221 --> 00:34:40.929
And one of the things
they're not so good

00:34:40.929 --> 00:34:45.790
is getting things right on
a really consistent basis

00:34:45.790 --> 00:34:48.380
over many, many repeats.

00:34:48.380 --> 00:34:51.790
So why not make the process
itself mistake-proof?

00:34:51.790 --> 00:34:52.989
This is a great example.

00:34:52.989 --> 00:34:55.989
It makes me feel much better
about being in a hospital.

00:34:55.989 --> 00:35:01.570
This is vacuum, and
this is oxygen. Now

00:35:01.570 --> 00:35:04.270
some things you want to hook up
to vacuum, and some things you

00:35:04.270 --> 00:35:08.260
want to hook up to oxygen.
And those look the same.

00:35:08.260 --> 00:35:10.390
And in fact, the
business end is the same.

00:35:10.390 --> 00:35:12.850
The coupler is the same.

00:35:12.850 --> 00:35:14.320
Obviously, hooking
the breather up

00:35:14.320 --> 00:35:17.920
to vacuum or the sort of
waste disposal thing up

00:35:17.920 --> 00:35:22.280
to pure oxygen that will light
it on fire, not a good idea.

00:35:22.280 --> 00:35:27.160
So there's a little stud so
that when you hook the thing up,

00:35:27.160 --> 00:35:30.620
it won't go into the wrong one.

00:35:30.620 --> 00:35:32.600
Very simple, very effective.

00:35:32.600 --> 00:35:37.640
That basic idea applies across
an amazing number of fields.

00:35:37.640 --> 00:35:40.310
Make it so you can't
hook it up wrong.

00:35:40.310 --> 00:35:44.690
There's a possibly apocryphal
story about airplanes.

00:35:44.690 --> 00:35:46.940
A lot of airplanes
these days fly by wire.

00:35:46.940 --> 00:35:49.850
Most of the controls go
through electronic components.

00:35:49.850 --> 00:35:53.840
They use the same couplers
because it's cheaper that way,

00:35:53.840 --> 00:35:55.370
so it's perfectly
possible to hook

00:35:55.370 --> 00:36:01.080
up the right-hand controls to
the left wing and vice versa.

00:36:01.080 --> 00:36:01.920
That's news, right?

00:36:01.920 --> 00:36:03.450
No, it's not possible anymore.

00:36:03.450 --> 00:36:06.570
That is something that has been
mistake-proofed, fortunately,

00:36:06.570 --> 00:36:08.220
long ago.

00:36:08.220 --> 00:36:11.700
Mistake-proofing the process.

00:36:11.700 --> 00:36:12.330
Checklist.

00:36:12.330 --> 00:36:13.950
This is a no brainer.

00:36:13.950 --> 00:36:17.790
But there's a great book
out in the medical field

00:36:17.790 --> 00:36:20.430
called Checklist
Revolution because it's

00:36:20.430 --> 00:36:22.680
revolutionary to use checklists.

00:36:22.680 --> 00:36:24.600
This, as a patient,
scares the heck out of me

00:36:24.600 --> 00:36:28.440
because in the aerospace
field, commercial airliners

00:36:28.440 --> 00:36:30.840
are astonishingly safe.

00:36:30.840 --> 00:36:33.270
They're probably the
safest complicated thing

00:36:33.270 --> 00:36:36.630
any civilization has
ever come up with.

00:36:36.630 --> 00:36:38.640
I'm sure they are, in fact.

00:36:38.640 --> 00:36:41.490
And one of the
reasons is that they

00:36:41.490 --> 00:36:43.980
are completely anal
retentive about checklists.

00:36:43.980 --> 00:36:45.060
Maintenance people do it.

00:36:45.060 --> 00:36:46.110
The pilots do it.

00:36:46.110 --> 00:36:48.760
Everybody operates off of lists.

00:36:48.760 --> 00:36:52.140
So you're not relying
on fallible human memory

00:36:52.140 --> 00:36:56.273
to make sure that the flaps
work before you take off.

00:36:56.273 --> 00:36:57.690
There's actually
a famous accident

00:36:57.690 --> 00:37:00.810
where they didn't bother
to do the checklist.

00:37:00.810 --> 00:37:03.660
And the flaps were not
working, and they took off,

00:37:03.660 --> 00:37:05.110
and it didn't work out so well.

00:37:05.110 --> 00:37:09.540
So very simple way of making
sure that complex processes

00:37:09.540 --> 00:37:13.490
are actually executed
correctly by fallible people.

00:37:13.490 --> 00:37:14.040
OK.

00:37:14.040 --> 00:37:17.040
We're going to do a quick
exercise in waste walking.

00:37:17.040 --> 00:37:19.800
I have handed out some dots.

00:37:19.800 --> 00:37:22.410
And we're going
to look at our map

00:37:22.410 --> 00:37:26.138
and decide if each one of
the steps and decisions--

00:37:26.138 --> 00:37:27.930
don't bother with the
weights because we're

00:37:27.930 --> 00:37:30.138
pretty sure those are
non-value added-- but the steps

00:37:30.138 --> 00:37:31.380
and decisions, for sure.

00:37:31.380 --> 00:37:33.360
Are they value added, green?

00:37:33.360 --> 00:37:34.950
Do something for the customer.

